\begin_layout Standard
Another way to model speciation, is by assuming that every timestep, there
 is a certain probability that a new lineage forms (instantaneously) or
 an existing lineage goes extinct.
 This simple model is called the birth-death model.
 The birth-death model has been suggested as null model for phylogenetic
 analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nee1994reconstructed,nee2001inferring,mooers1997inferring"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simulate a continuous time birth-death model, one must take the following
 steps
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gillespie1977exact"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the time to pass 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 at which the next event will happen, which is dependent on the number of
 extant lineages 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{extant}$
\end_inset

, time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, birth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, and death rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\leftarrow rexp(N_{extant}(\lambda+\mu))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $rexp$
\end_inset

 is a random number drawn from an exponential distribution with its growth
 rate supplied as the argument
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increase the current time: 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leftarrow t+\delta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Determine what will happen.
 The probability of a birth event 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{birth}=\frac{\lambda}{\lambda+\mu}$
\end_inset

, whereas the probability of a death event is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{death}=\frac{\mu}{\lambda+\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Draw a random number between zero and one (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{birth}+p_{death}=1$
\end_inset

) to choose which event occurs.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

