\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Comparing-models"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to select the best model? And what exactly do we mean by 'best'? This
 is already an old, but still important question.
 Anscombe's Quartet, published in 1972, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "anscombe1973graphs"

\end_inset

 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Anscombe's-Quartet"

\end_inset

) is a nice example of the equally good fit of a linear model to several
 very different data sets, with (close to) equal mean and variance in terms
 of sum of error squared.
 When looking at the data, however, the fit looses its sensibility.
 Anscombe argues we should always visualize the data, instead of fitting
 a line or curve through it blindly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "anscombe1973graphs"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

