\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this research, it is the other way around: it is about selecting the
 model behind the data.
 And there is ample literature on model selection (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "burnham2002model,wit2012all"

\end_inset

).
 In this context, 'What is the best model?' has two meanings (after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit2012all"

\end_inset

): (1) which modelling procedure will, with sufficient data, identify the
 true model? and (2) based on the data, which model lies closest to the
 true model? Unsurprisingly, there are many ways to compare models, each
 comparison having its own pros and cons: Akaike Information Criterion,
 Bayes Factor, Bayesian Information Criterion, Deviance Information Criterion,
 false discovery rate, Focused Information Criterion, likelihood-ratio test,
 Mallows 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

, minimum description length, posterior-predictive tests, Widely Applicable
 Information Criterion, not naming close derivatives such as 
\begin_inset Formula $AIC_{c}$
\end_inset

 of members of this incomplete list 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit2012all,green1995reversible,nylander2005model"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important frequentist test is the Akaike Information Criterion
 (AIC, as discussed in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Akaike-Information-Criterion"

\end_inset

), the most important Bayesian test is the Bayesian Information Criterion
 (BIC).
 For the frequentist approach, I will describe the common hierarchical likelihoo
d-ratio test (hLRT) and the AIC, for the Bayesian approach I will describe
 the Bayes Factor and BIC.
 Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "posada2004model"

\end_inset

 has a nice comparison of the hLRT, Bayes Factor and AIC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These techniques can yield the best model, but this may not be an adequate
 model.
 This can be tested by penelized likelihood, parametric bootstrap and posterior
 predictive checks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nylander2005model"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hierarchical likelihood-ratio test
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Hierarchical-likelihood-ratio-test"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frequentist's toolbox is commonly equipped with the hierarchical likelihood-
ratio test (hLRT) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "posada2004model"

\end_inset

.
 An hLRT can be used for models that have a known maximum likelihood function
 and are nested.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a model that serves as a null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a more elaborate model 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 that may or may not fit the observed data significantly better.
 The models must be nested: it must be possible that a certain parameter
 combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 reduces it to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 For example, an Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process can be reduced to a Brownian
 motion by setting its mean reversion rate to zero.
 Let the parameters fitting the null model best (as found by maximum likelihood)
 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta_{0}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are the best parameters for the alternative model, on the same observed
 data 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The test statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is then defined as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "posada2004model,salemi2003phylogenetic,nylander2005model"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ALSO: The phylogenetic handbook, page 348
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta=2\left(\mathcal{L}(\hat{\theta_{1}}\mid X)-\mathcal{L}(\hat{\theta_{0}}\mid X)\right)\label{eq:LikelihoodRatioTest}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(\theta{}_{i}\mid X)$
\end_inset

 is the maximized log likelihood of (the parameters of) model 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 given the data 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, called the deviance, follows approximately a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 This distribution has as many degrees of freedom as the alternative model
 has more parameters than the null model.
 If the LRT is located in the rejection area of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 distribution the null hypothesis is rejected and the alternative model
 is said to have a significantly higher likelihood.
\end_layout

