\begin_layout Subsection
Akaike Information Criterion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Akaike-Information-Criterion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most commonly used tool to compare models by the frequentist is the
 Akaike Information Criterion (AIC).
 Every model has an AIC dependent on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 number of parameters it has and a maximum log likelihood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(\hat{\theta_{0}}\mid X)$
\end_inset

 as shown by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AIC"

\end_inset

 (from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "posada2004model,nylander2005model,lemey2009phylogenetic"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The phylogenetic handbook, page 351
\end_layout

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
AIC=2k-2\mathcal{L}(\hat{\theta}\mid X)\label{eq:AIC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferred model is the model with the lowest AIC.
 The first term, 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

, has a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 to correct for asymptotic bias (thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is not arbitrary at all).
 In a phylogenetic context, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 may also include an estimated tree topology.
 If this is so, then twice the number of taxa minus three mujst be added
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lemey2009phylogenetic"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The phylogenetic handbook, page 351
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The second term, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mathcal{L}(\hat{\theta}\mid X)$
\end_inset

, also has a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 with the function of making the entire term asymptotically chi-squared
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "burnham2002model"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pp 64
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The AIC assumes a large sample size.
 If the sample size is small, the closely related 
\begin_inset Formula $AIC_{c}$
\end_inset

 can take the sample size into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AICs can also be compared by their weights, where the AIC weight of model
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{AIC_{i}}=e^{-\frac{1}{2}AIC_{i}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the chance 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, that the model with AIC score 
\begin_inset Formula $AIC_{i}$
\end_inset

 is correct, equals: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\left(AIC_{i}\right)=\frac{W_{AIC_{i}}}{\sum\left(W_{AIC}\right)}\label{eq:AIC_model_probability}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bayes factors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Bayes-factors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bayes factors can be viewed as the Bayesian analog of an LRT (the latter
 being described in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Hierarchical-likelihood-ratio-test"

\end_inset

).
 The Bayes factor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of two models, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{j}$
\end_inset

 equals the ratio between the model posteriors 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(D\mid M_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D\mid M_{j})$
\end_inset

 that use parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 with data 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{ij}=\frac{Pr(D\mid M_{i})}{Pr(D\mid M_{j})}=\frac{\intop Pr\left(\theta_{1}\mid M_{1}\right)Pr\left(D\mid\theta_{1},M_{1}\right)d\theta_{1}}{\intop Pr\left(\theta_{2}\mid M_{2}\right)Pr\left(D\mid\theta_{2},M_{2}\right)d\theta_{2}}\label{eq:BayesFactor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A model's posterior 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr$
\end_inset

