\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) is an information criterion closely
 related to the AIC (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Akaike-Information-Criterion"

\end_inset

).
 The preferred model is the model with the lowest BIC.
 A model 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 has a BIC dependent on maximum log-likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(\hat{\theta}\right)$
\end_inset

(where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

 are the parameters yielding the maximum likelihood) for a parameter space
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 dimensions and sample size of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, as shown in equation (from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit2012all"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
BIC(\mathcal{M})=2l\left(\hat{\theta}\right)+p\cdot ln(n)\label{eq:BIC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in phylogenetics, the sample size is an open area for research
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nylander2005model"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Wat zeggen zij hier verder over?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Daar zeggen ze niks over
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Choosing the lowest BIC is one way to select a best model, a more Bayesian
 approach will be to compare model weights 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\mathcal{M})$
