\begin_layout Section
Trait stochasticity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Trait-stochasticity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine a species having a trait, and that trait value changing in time.
 The trait value is changed by recombination and mutation, two processes
 with a stochastic property.
 A trait value in time will be different with or without selection, thus
 there are already two types of stochastic processes.
 A neutral trait can be modeled as a Brownian motion, which is an undirected
 random process.
 It is the ancestor of all other stochastic processes and discussed in chapter
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Brownian-Motion"

\end_inset

.
 Traits that are non-neutral and have an optimum value can be modeled by
 an Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process, which modifies the Brownian motion by adding
 a certain target mean to converge to.
 Because of its general use, it is discussed in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Ornstein-Uhlenbeck"

\end_inset

.
 There are also other models I will only briefly mention here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A single-burst (SB) model assumes that the mean of a Brownian motion can
 have a major shift once 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uyeda2011million"

\end_inset

, for example when an adaptive radiation takes place
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A multiple-burst (MB) model is an Brownian motion that can have multiple
 major shifts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uyeda2011million"

\end_inset

, for example when adaptive radiations takes place.
 Close to this is the punctuated equilibrium (PE) model which assumes that
 most trait fluctuations take place at speciation.
 There is some controversy around PE, as Pennell et al argue that the PE
 model tries to capture multiple conceptually distinct ideas (evolution
 being pulsed or gradual, most trait evolution occurring during radiation
 or not) in a single framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennell2014there"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to understand the process governing a trait value in time.
 A trait value following a Brownian motion is neutral, thus has no biological
 forces acting on it.
 Detecting the stochastic process underlying noisy data increases our focus
 on investigating traits that have a larger biological relevance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Brownian Motion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Brownian-Motion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Brownian motion (BM) model is described by the Wiener process, a continuous-ti
me stochastic process.
 A Wiener process has changes that are independent and drawn from a normal
 distribution with mean zero and constant variance.
 This results in an expected mean of zero.
 An example of a Brownian motion described by James Brown in 1827 is the
 motion of a pollen grain through water.
 The stochastic differential equation for the BM model is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dx_{t}=\sigma dW_{t}\label{eq:BM-SDE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value changing in time is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by rate 
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The only term is a noise term, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the volatility or noise strength and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process.
 The exact solution of this SDE is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM-recurrent"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{t+\delta}=x_{i}+\sigma\sqrt{\delta}N_{0,1}\label{eq:BM-recurrent}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM-recurrent"

\end_inset

 is a recurrence equation that calculates the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\Delta$
\end_inset

 from the current value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at timepoint 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The equation allows for a sampling time 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, which is positive and can be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 An example run is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-Brownian-motion-run"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

