\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma^{2}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-x_{i-1}\right)^{2}\label{eq:MaxLikelihoodVolatilityBm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimated volatility 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum likelihood estimates given the set of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The estimated parameters will differ from the true known parameters (to
 generate the data), which is caused by the random noise of the Wiener process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ornstein-Uhlenbeck
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Ornstein-Uhlenbeck"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU) model is a stochastic process that is attracted
 to a mean value and it is a member of the single stationary peak (SSP)
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harmon2010early"

\end_inset

.
 An example OU process is a particle under Brownian motion experiencing
 friction.
 The stochastic differential equation for the OE model is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dx_{t}=\theta\left(\mu-x_{t}\right)dt+\sigma dW_{t}\label{eq:OU-SDE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value changing in time is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by rate 
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is attracted to long-term mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 sets the direction of the slope of the SDE, which allows 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to decrease its distance to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The strength 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is determined by the mean reversion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0$
\end_inset

.
 The first term would could 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 with a speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 The second term is a noise term, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the volatility or noise strength and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process.
 Note that a Wiener process is a synonym for Brownian motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exact solution of this SDE is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OU-recurrence"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{t+1}=x_{i}e^{-\theta\delta}+\theta\left(1-e^{-\theta\delta}\right)+\sigma\sqrt{\frac{1-e^{-2\theta\delta}}{2\theta}}N_{0,1}\label{eq:OU-recurrence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OU-recurrence"

\end_inset

 is a recurrence equation that calculates the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\delta$
\end_inset

 from the current value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at timepoint 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The equation allows for a sampling time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, which can be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
